{
    "level": "A2",
    "intro": "In this topic you will learn the difference between <strong>-ed</strong> and <strong>-ing</strong> adjectives: <strong>-ed</strong> describes a person’s feeling, and <strong>-ing</strong> describes the thing, situation, or person that causes it.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "FEELING",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "<strong>-ed</strong> = how someone feels:",
            "example": "I am bored."
        },
        {
            "label": "CAUSE",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "<strong>-ing</strong> = what causes the feeling:",
            "example": "The film is boring."
        },
        {
            "label": "SAME ROOT",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "The pair often comes from the same root: bored / boring, interested / interesting, tired / tiring.",
            "example": "She is interested in an interesting book."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Common pairs",
    "intro": "It is best to learn these adjectives in pairs.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "feeling / cause",
            "title": "bored / boring",
            "subtitle": "I am bored. / The lesson is boring."
        },
        {
            "label": "feeling / cause",
            "title": "interested / interesting",
            "subtitle": "We are interested. / The topic is interesting."
        },
        {
            "label": "feeling / cause",
            "title": "excited / exciting",
            "subtitle": "They are excited. / The trip is exciting."
        },
        {
            "label": "feeling / cause",
            "title": "tired / tiring",
            "subtitle": "I am tired. / The journey is tiring."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. How it works",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "When we talk about people",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "If you describe a person’s <strong>emotion or state</strong>, you usually need <strong>-ed</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I am really tired after work.",
                    "ua": "I am really tired after work."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She felt embarrassed in class.",
                    "ua": "She felt embarrassed in class."
                },
                {
                    "en": "We were surprised by the news.",
                    "ua": "We were surprised by the news."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "When we talk about a thing or situation",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "If something <strong>causes</strong> the emotion, you usually need <strong>-ing</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "The lecture was boring.",
                    "ua": "The lecture was boring."
                },
                {
                    "en": "It was an exciting match.",
                    "ua": "It was an exciting match."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The instructions are confusing.",
                    "ua": "The instructions are confusing."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Compare the pair",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "One ending changes the whole logic of the sentence.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I am bored. / The film is boring.",
                    "ua": "I am bored. / The film is boring."
                },
                {
                    "en": "They are excited. / The trip is exciting.",
                    "ua": "They are excited. / The trip is exciting."
                },
                {
                    "en": "He is confused. / The map is confusing.",
                    "ua": "He is confused. / The map is confusing."
                }
            ],
            "note": "Ask yourself first: is this a feeling or the cause of the feeling?"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. Common mistakes",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Mistake 1",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Using boring for a person who feels bored.",
            "wrong": "I am boring.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">I am bored.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 2",
            "color": "amber",
            "title": "Using bored for a film or lesson.",
            "wrong": "The lesson is bored.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">The lesson is boring.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 3",
            "color": "sky",
            "title": "Mixing the pair.",
            "wrong": "She is interesting in art.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">She is interested in art.</span>"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "4. Quick summary",
    "items": [
        "<strong>-ed</strong> describes a person’s feeling or state.",
        "<strong>-ing</strong> describes the thing, event, or person that causes the feeling.",
        "Learn the pairs together: bored / boring, excited / exciting, interested / interesting.",
        "If a person feels something, you usually need <strong>-ed</strong>.",
        "If something causes the emotion, you usually need <strong>-ing</strong>."
    ]
}

